# The Machine

For all experiments, there is a warmup time, when more and more energy is being fed into the machine. (human)

There are adjustable controls for the characters to set: how far in space the teleport goes (distance from the machine), and how "far" in multiverse the teleport goes (i.e. how many adjacent universes get hopped). (human)

The machine can only communicate forward along the line of universes; they cannot communicate backwards. (human)

The multiverses are arranged along a 1-dimensional line. There is an adjacent universe forward and behind the current universe. (human)

With more power (or some kind of adjustable control), they can communicate with universe 2, 3, 4, etc. universes ahead. They can never communicate behind. (human)

We don't know if there is an infinite number of universes or a finite amount. (human)

The causality problem of how the experiment "starts" (e.g., "who was the first universe to start the experiment?" or "wouldn't the experiment have never started if it also requires input from the previous universe?") is fundamentally unsolvable and stalls progress on formulating plot ideas. Instead, run with the working assumption that "these things magically just started" and focus on how the number/information would propagate forward. Focus on the propagation, and also on the "end state" of an effectively infinite-scale experiment. (human)

Leaning towards a non-infinite number of universes, but a very large number of universes. Sometimes the main characters' universe is near the end of the loop (i.e., experiencing the "end state" of the experiment); sometimes they are near the start of the experiment; sometimes they may be in the middle. (human)

If the characters for a particular experiment are at the start or end of the experimental loop, it's less interesting from an audience standpoint, since the twists and interesting results are near the end of the multiverse loop. Thus a clever mechanism is needed for universes to communicate to each other the results of the previous experiment they just ran. (human)

OPEN QUESTION: Information being sent in each experiment needs to have a feedback section, two events back to back. Do the two events happen during two back-to-back experiments, or within the same experiment? (human)

All machines must fire and receive the swap at the same time, with no propagation delay between universes. But this may limit divergence. (human)

If the machine is transparent, they can catch a glimpse or preview of the image before it fully teleports in. (human)

In general, devise a mechanism for communication to propagate forward in time, across multiple universes (and potentially across multiple experiments). (human)

There must be a forward cause-and-effect chain in order for divergence to happen. The cause and effect go "forward" through adjacent universes. (human)

The multiverses start with effectively 0 randomness/divergence. The challenge is how to introduce divergence into a set of multiverses that have been perfectly identical for 10 billion years. A minute level of randomness — like a random particle decay that happens in some universes but not others — would quickly blow up into a butterfly effect, causing all multiverses to rapidly diverge over the normal 10-billion-year age of the universe. So the story needs to go from a world of effectively 0 randomness, to a world with just 1 or 2 small instances of randomness. These introductions of small randomness become butterfly effects of their own, but only branching out from those 1 or 2 small divergences. The challenge is how to pierce a set of multiverses with 0 randomness/divergence into a world where divergence can emerge. A semi-legitimate technobabble solution is needed. (human)

The machine generates a new set of fundamental particles called "Schneider particles". These particles are the multiverse-hopping/breaking elements of the story. Schneider particles don't otherwise occur naturally in such concentrations — effectively, in the 10 billion years of the universe, these particle concentrations have never occurred naturally. (human)

Normally in science, stars produce extreme particles and physics events that we then try to reproduce in the lab. Schneider particles are the opposite: a completely bespoke, fundamentally man-made phenomenon. (human)

To rip a hole in the dimensions is more about "clearing" or "aligning" particles in the 3rd dimension. If you create a uniform area without the default random noise of particles, it opens up a space for the 4th dimensional Schneider particles to come through. Schneider particles are always bouncing off of the 3rd dimension because of the noisy wall of particles. The machine allows the Schneider particles to slip in. OPEN QUESTION: This implies something like a vacuum chamber level of "clean space" within the machine — so how would it make sense to have objects put into the machine without disrupting this clean alignment? (human)

The presence of Schneider particles is meant to be just an intermediary particle to facilitate the portal phenomena. The Schneider particles aren't the fun part of the experiments. Characters should move past the Schneider particles quickly once the portal effects are discovered. The ability for the characters to measure Schneider particles ends up being just a tool for measurements, visually like dials and lights on the machines and computers blinking or turning. (human)

What matter is in the machine is sent "forward" to the next universe. That forward-bound matter appears at the external location in the forward universe (not inside that universe's machine). What appears inside the machine is matter from the backward universe, from that universe's external location. (human)

The decision of what to put in the machine must happen after you receive something from another universe. Or the other way around. (human)

It's not a one-way teleport, but a swap of matter between universes. (human)

It's not a swap from the same physical space in the universe. The teleport happens in two nearby places: space A is inside the machine, and space B is external to the machine. (human)

The primary part of the machine is a large hollow cylinder. It has a door/lock on one end to put things in and out of the chamber. (human)

Another part next to the machine bombards the chamber with special new physics high speed particles. This is the energy that is needed to do the interdimensional swap. (human)

OPEN QUESTION: how big is the chamber of the machine? (human)

OPEN QUESTION: energy is applied to the matter in the chamber, this makes sense that it then propels the chamber matter to the next dimension. But, if no particles/energies are being applied to the external spot, then how does it make sense that the external matter is able to propel to inside the chamber of the next dimension? (human)

Maybe the machine creates a wormhole in both directions at the same time, extending backward to the previous universe's external spot, and extending forward to the forward universe's external spot. Call this the 'double reach' model. (human)

The swap is a convenient feature to help prevent matter from transporting into a spot with existing matter. But it also requires a perfect coordination of all machines in all worlds. (human)

What if, in the 'double reach' model, one arm of the reach connects first before the other (like more energy rate in one arm over the other)? Could this mechanism be used to do delayed swaps? (human)

The team figures out a way to induce this causal delay, but only for about 10 seconds. (human)

Sometimes in the experiments, the object appears at the distant location immediately, sometimes with a few seconds delay, and sometimes a few seconds earlier. There is a bit of randomness to it. OPEN QUESTION: Would all universes experience the same delay for each given experiment, or would each universe get a different delay within the same experiment? (human)

Maybe, in the 2-arm machine approach, if one arm connects before the other, that space gets "frozen" in place before the other connects. (human)

The chain of all arms across all universes can be visualized like a river or jet stream current that flows through the multiverse. (human)

OPEN QUESTION: If matter coming in threatens to teleport onto existing matter that hasn't left yet, maybe it gets pushed to the side in 3 dimensions — like it gets popped to the side. (human)

If all universes turn on their machines at the same time, then all swaps happen at the same time. (human)

