OPEN QUESTION: If the backward universe didn't turn on their machine, what appears in your machine? Vacuum? (human)

It is an important mechanism for the multiverse to be able to share results with each other. One of the first experiments they can do to demonstrate this is to ask "what was your result from the previous experiment?" In the example of the 'counting experiment', they see that the previous universe counted -1 value compared to what they had gotten. (human)

Experiment idea: the team tries to count the full number of universes by writing a number on a piece of paper, sending it forward, and having the next universe add 1 before sending it onward. (human)

Possible outcomes for the counting experiment: (human)
- The number effectively stays "2" because all universes are incrementing in sync at the same time. (human)
- The number grows so large there is no room left on the paper; the visible written value stabilizes as a truncated value. (human)
- The number grows so large that teammates cannot finish reading it aloud before the next write/send step. (human)
- They switch to tally marks instead of numeric digits. (human)

When they do the tally mark experiment, using a pencil, the whole page is marked solid with graphite, and even tattered and falling apart. (human)

For the clarity of the counting/tally experiments, they must start with a blank paper. With rules like "If there's a blank paper, add a tally." (human)

Some counting experiments could have a stopping condition. Like: count up to 10; if we get a 10, place a blank paper. Their universe keeps consistently getting an answer like 5. Then they run progressively different count numbers — count up to 11, they keep getting 9. Through a greater and greater combination of counting experiments, they manage to get an exact (or near-exact) count of universes. It is finite, something like 12 billion. (human) OPEN QUESTION: Do the math — would all universes running the same experiment be able to conclude their place in the multiverse ring?

