# Higher Dimensions

In addition to the concept of multiverses, as the medium that connects the multiverses, the space containing all of the multiverses is extra-dimensional — more than 3 spatial dimensions, possibly as many as 10 (as suggested by string theory). Thinking in the space of higher dimensions allows consideration of different pathways for why things like causality can be violated. A shape, path, or line in higher dimensions represents normal causality taking place at the lower 3 dimensions — or not occurring in those 3 dimensions. (human)

Laws of physics (e.g., "conservation of energy," "causality") can be assigned to different levels of the higher dimensions. When characters witness a violation of these laws, they can deduce that they have been traveling through those higher dimensions. (human)

TODO: Research a list of physics laws that seem to be fundamental to the universe — things like CPT symmetry, conservation of energy, conservation of momentum. Also find statements about the fundamentally random nature of the quantum world (e.g., quantum indeterminacy, radioactive decay). Since the story will violate some laws of physics as the "twist" of the plot, carefully track which laws to treat as sacred and which to break. (human)

If there is a non-consistent effect of force that emerges in the 3 dimensions, the source of that inconsistency comes from the higher dimensions. Like an inconsistent wind or weather that is flowing or sloshing around in the higher dimension. This can be the mechanism for one universe "starting" before the others. (human)

A single universe could be the tip of the "starting" point. And which specific multiverse acts as the "start" could change by the minute. There could also be multiple universes that act as the starting point, like causality nucleation sites. The propagation of causality could then spread out from the nucleation sites to the adjacent universes, but quickly spreading and covering all of the universes. (human)

If a shifting nucleation site is introduced for the experiments, would this cause varying results of the same experiment — for example, in the counting experiment, getting different counting results? No — this is not a force that drives the actual end results, but is a higher-level concept of "kick-starting an experiment." Since the experiments are basically an exercise in infinity math, or like taking an equation as it asymptotically approaches its limits. (human)

Would there be something special about the "first" universe in an experiment? It wouldn't be count 1 in the universe (this force doesn't drive that). Instead, the first universe would be the one able to set causality delays in an experiment. (human)

Causality should be thought of like a force wave in a higher plane, like an ocean of waves. Causality is usually in an equilibrium, appearing to be something linear, but it's the average of many different little waves evening out. (human)

With the theory of infinities in this universe, they end up in equilibrium states, but how exactly they start can be a bit flexible. Universe A is the original "start" of an effect, but as the infinity effect propagates around the ring of multiverses, the causality cascading could rewrite universe B to appear to be the start of the effect (for example, in the "counting experiments"). This means the story doesn't have to worry too much about describing who/where the first universe in the experiment is — just focusing on the end-state equilibrium. (human)

Hammer in the unintuitive idea that "it doesn't matter how it started, it only matters how it ends." (human)

Regardless of which universe nucleates, there would still be rippling causality effects across all universes. They would all roughly take the same time to equilibrialize. (human)

When two adjacent universes don't have direct causality lined up (e.g., a count-5 universe is next to a count-10 universe), that distance in continuity is like a tension or a force that naturally wants to pull adjacent continuities into alignment. This is a style of "self-correcting universe." (human)

Analogy: A still pool of water can be disturbed from any point on the edge. Ultimately, any way you start the disturbance, after a couple of rebounding waves, it all ends up in the same equilibrium. Most pool shapes don't have this start-invariant effect, but characters can show they are researching special shapes that do have this effect. Also related: multiple metronomes on a moving table will all synchronize themselves. The speed and nature of the convergence implies the interconnectedness and the shape of the whole system. Later, when characters witness convergences and invariance in the multi-dimensions, they can fall back on these analogies, like "that is the special shape of the universe." (human)

Analogy: We use pings from earthquakes rippling through the core of the earth to deduce the inner workings of the core. It's effectively a 1 or 2 dimensional signal used to reconstruct a 3 dimensional thing. (human)

If the 'rippling towards equilibrium' approach is used for the multiverse, then there is a small period of time at the start when causality is a little chaotic. OPEN QUESTION: Does this happen super fast (on the order of milliseconds, something characters can only see using a slow-motion camera), or does it take like 10 seconds to resolve so characters with their own eyes can see a piece of paper flicker with different values? (human)

OPEN QUESTION: If characters can see a flickering causality on the paper, do they see a fast linear progression of values, or do they see random jumps between values? (human)

Analogy: Someone showing the full path of their life on Google Maps — the shape of their life. This can be used later when discussing causality, like causality is a "shape." "Everything has a shape, we just need to figure out what it is." (human)

The Schneider particles themselves could be sourced from the higher dimensions. If wanting to have crazy effects appear in the 3rd dimension, characters don't need to use only materials from the 3rd dimension to accomplish this. Instead they could be tapping into flows of materials and forces ebbing and flowing from a higher dimension — opening up a hole in the 3rd/4th dimension layer, and letting the particles "pour" in. The energy that the machine puts in is used to rip the hole open at different levels and angles, dictating the location of the second hole. (human)

Ripping a Schneider hole might only be started by the machine at a single spot, but actually multiple holes in multiple 3rd dimensional spatial spots open up at the same time (or nearly the same time, with a little bit of delay). The source of the secondary (or possibly 3rd) holes could show up at a proportionate distance, like a light diffusion pattern or the light interference pattern of a double-slit experiment. (human)

Should the multidimensional diffusion ripples cause multiple holes across multiple universes, like 3rd order, 4th order ripples, that get exponentially weaker, but still have some slight trans-3rd dimensional effect? (human)

Should each extra hole reach out to the next adjacent universe, meaning each experiment is actually touching 2 or 3 multiverses at the same time? Or maybe each extra hole is traversing in another higher layer of spatial dimensions (4th, 5th, etc.), which does manifest as different physical places in the 3rd dimension, but is otherwise punching through other physics-violating things. (human)

The holes are not meant to be a very clean, clear-cut phenomenon; they're a little messy, like a real-world phenomenon would be. (human)

The extra 2nd and 3rd order holes get smaller and smaller, down to basically microscopic. (human)
